AB  - In cases in which indigenous resources comprise a small amount of a state's energy supplies, money spent on energy is transferred to export economies, reducing local spending on goods and services.  Prevention of this transfer via conservation increases household disposable income, which in turn, impacts areas like the local tax base, sales, and jobs.  It follows that a strong relationship can exist between energy efficiency and economic development.  In some areas, optimal energy conservation can be achieved without government intervention due to market incentives.  Nevertheless, institutional barriers in the rental sector contribute to a lack of thermal integrity in structures often inhabited by those who can least afford energy price increases.  The problems that are associated with achieving energy efficiency in rental housing are reviewed, and the approaches used by local governments to overcome barriers are reported.  The experience of Ithaca, New York, serves as an example.
